But when rich mortals start turning up dead with fang marks on their necks, Valens, a vampyre slave-turned-Roman soldier, plunges into the blood-soaked underworld of Rome to capture the Pluto's Kiss Killer. If he can prove himself, he'll earn rank and riches beyond what anyone this side of the Tiber has ever seen! But if he fails, he just might find himself on top of the pile of bodies! Don't miss this crimson-red, 6-issue thriller that mixes the undead intrigue of True Blood with the brutal Roman action and political drama of Spartacus from newcomers Stuart C. description:
Dynamite entertainment, under the license of King Features Syndicate, started this new series of the Last Phantom that spins around a completely different story compared to the conventional Phantom stories. Alex Ross and Blackest Night artists Joe Prado and Fabiano Neves have presented new the Ghost who walks in a whole new way, while Scott Beatty has scripted it.

The story first begins with no Phantom. The 21st Phantom was the last of the series. Kit Walker Jr. refused to take up the mantle as the masked crime fighter and is on a comfortable ride of life and family, while handling the day-to-day affairs of the Walkabout Foundation, an organization created by one of the previous Walkers to help support charities in Bengala, and the surrounding nations of Africa. This volume of comic books describes the Kit Walker Jr.'s course and whether he will continue to lead that comfortable life or does the destiny bring him back to be the Guardian of the Eastern Dark.

Collected Editions

  • The Last Phantom: Ghostwalk (#1 to #6)
  • The Last Phantom: Jungle Rules (#7 to #12)

Annuals

deck: A Heavy Metal Special series published intermittently throughout the year.
description:
A spin-off of Heavy Metal Magazine, these are the specials released throughout the years as a separate publication.

The numbering is confusing as some issues are numbered in the main series, and some in both. The indicia should be consulted to know if an issue is released as part of the main series or a special. The specials had a separate volume numbering, beginning in 1989 with The Venus Interface which is numbered Vol. 5, number 4.

The number of special issues that have been released is as follows:

  • 1989: 1 Issue
  • 1990 - 1991: None
  • 1992: 1 Issue
  • 1993 - 1998: 2 Issues
  • 1999 - 2002: 3 Issues
  • 2003: 4 Issues
  • 2004 - 2007: 3 Issues
  • 2008 - 2010: 3 Issues (New numbering, see note below)
  • 2011: 2 Issues
  • 2012 - Present: None

The issues are numbered by yyyynn, with y being the year they were released and n being the number for that year, for example the second special released in 1999 would be indexed as 199902.

The Fall 2008 Special and beyond combine with the main series and take on the volume numbering of the main series which is now subscribed to as a "nine issues a year" book. Later issues are again part of this series, or both.
name: Heavy Metal Special

deck: Dubbed, "The Beano's BIG brother", BeanoMAX was a monthly publication aimed at an older age-range than its weekly counterpart.
description: Dubbed The Beano's BIG brother, BeanoMAX was a monthly publication aimed at an older age-range than its weekly counterpart, with more feature content alongside the comic strips. In the latter half of it's run, it was home to Wallace and Gromit. It ran for 79 issues, ending in June 2013. It replaced The Beano Summer Special and was replaced by the 100% Official Dennis the Menace and Gnasher Megazine, a tie-in to the 2013 Dennis the Menace and Gnasher cartoon, which retained MAX's numbering in order to avoid retailers rejecting the new comic launch.
name: BeanoMAX
